(42, 13, 16, 43, 8, 44, 44, 'whom Satan hath bound', 'Connection of Bondage and Freedom', 'This connection highlights the theme of bondage and liberation. In Luke, the woman is described as being bound by Satan, while in John, the devil is characterized as a liar and a murderer, emphasizing the destructive nature of evil.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 16, 44, 13, 26, 26, 'daughter of Abraham', 'Connection of Abraham''s Children', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''children of Abraham'' in both passages. Luke emphasizes the healing of a daughter of Abraham, while Acts addresses the audience as ''children of the stock of Abraham.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 16, 40, 4, 10, 10, 'Satan hath bound', 'Connection of Spiritual Authority', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus over Satan''s bondage. Both passages emphasize the power of God to free individuals from spiritual oppression, as seen in the healing of the woman and Jesus'' command to Satan.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 60, 3, 16, 16, NULL, 'Shame and Good Conduct', 'This connection highlights the theme of shame experienced by adversaries in both passages. In Luke, adversaries are ashamed after Jesus'' words, while in 1 Peter, those who falsely accuse are also made ashamed due to the good conduct of believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 19, 132, 18, 18, 'all his adversaries were ashamed', 'Shame and Glory Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of shame experienced by adversaries in both passages. In Luke, adversaries are ''ashamed,'' while in Psalms, enemies are ''clothed with shame,'' contrasting their fate with the flourishing of the righteous.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 2, 15, 11, 11, 'glorious things that were done by him', 'Glory and Wonders of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s glory and the wonders He performs. Both passages emphasize the reaction of people to God''s glorious deeds, with Luke noting the rejoicing of the people and Exodus proclaiming God''s holiness and wonders.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 19, 40, 14, 14, 'all his adversaries were ashamed', 'Shame and Rejoicing Contrast', 'This connection highlights the theme of shame experienced by adversaries in both passages. In Luke, adversaries are ashamed after Jesus'' words, while in Psalms, those seeking harm are called to be ashamed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 23, 4, 2, 2, 'glorious things that were done by him', 'Connection of Glory and Beauty', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of glory, with Luke highlighting the ''glorious things'' done by Jesus and Isaiah describing the ''beautiful and glorious'' branch of the Lord. This connection highlights the manifestation of divine glory in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 23, 45, 24, 24, 'all his adversaries were ashamed', 'Shame and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of shame experienced by adversaries in both passages. In Luke, adversaries are ''ashamed,'' while Isaiah speaks of those ''incensed against him'' being ''ashamed,'' linking their responses to the Lord''s righteousness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 17, 42, 14, 6, 6, 'all his adversaries were ashamed', 'Response to Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the inability of adversaries to respond to Jesus'' authority. In Luke 13:17, adversaries are ashamed, while in Luke 14:6, they cannot answer him again.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 18, 41, 4, 30, 34, 'whereunto shall I resemble it?', 'Comparison of the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the question of how to liken the kingdom of God. They present a metaphorical comparison, with Luke introducing the inquiry and Mark providing a specific example of the mustard seed.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 18, 40, 13, 31, 32, 'kingdom of God like', 'Connection of Kingdom Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of the kingdom of God. Luke 13:18 poses a question about the kingdom, while Matthew 13:31-32 provides a parable illustrating its growth from small beginnings.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 18, 42, 17, 21, 21, 'kingdom of God', 'Connection of the Kingdom of God', 'This connection highlights the nature of the kingdom of God. In both passages, the kingdom is described in terms of its presence and essence, suggesting it is not confined to a physical location but is instead an internal reality.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 18, 42, 13, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the inquiry into the nature of the kingdom of God. The repeated question format in each verse highlights a thematic continuity in exploring this concept.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 18, 40, 13, 24, 24, 'kingdom of God', 'Connection of Kingdom Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of God. Both passages use the phrase ''the kingdom'' to introduce parables that illustrate its nature.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 18, 25, 2, 13, 13, 'whereunto shall I resemble it?', 'Kingdom and Comfort Imagery', 'This connection highlights the use of metaphorical language in both passages. Luke 13:18 asks what the kingdom of God is like, while Lamentations 2:13 seeks to liken the daughter of Jerusalem to something for comfort.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 27, 4, 12, 12, 'the fowls of the air lodged in the branches of it', 'Growth and Provision Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of a tree providing shelter and sustenance. The ''fowls of the air'' in Luke and the ''fowls of the heaven'' in Daniel illustrate the theme of nature''s provision.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 26, 17, 22, 24, 'the fowls of the air lodged', 'Growth and Shelter Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of growth and shelter provided by trees. The mustard seed in Luke grows into a great tree, while Ezekiel describes a cedar that provides shelter for birds, highlighting a theme of divine provision and flourishing.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 27, 2, 44, 45, 'great tree', 'Kingdom Growth and Permanence', 'This connection highlights the theme of the establishment and growth of God''s kingdom. Both passages emphasize the idea of a kingdom that grows significantly and stands forever, symbolizing divine authority and permanence.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 38, 2, 11, 11, 'great tree', 'Growth and Inclusion of Nations', 'This connection highlights the theme of growth and expansion in both passages. The mustard seed''s growth into a great tree symbolizes the inclusion of many nations as God''s people, as stated in Zechariah.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 40, 13, 31, 32, 'the fowls of the air lodged in the branches of it', 'Mustard Seed Parable Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the mustard seed''s growth into a tree, illustrating the expansive nature of the kingdom of heaven. The imagery of birds lodging in the branches further connects the two parables.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 41, 4, 31, 32, 'the fowls of the air lodged in the branches of it', 'Mustard Seed Parable Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the growth of a mustard seed into a large tree, illustrating the theme of small beginnings leading to significant outcomes. The imagery of birds lodging in the branches further connects the two accounts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 19, 23, 9, 7, 7, 'great tree', 'Growth of God''s Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of growth and establishment in both passages. Luke 13:19 describes the mustard seed growing into a great tree, while Isaiah 9:7 speaks of the increase of God''s government and peace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 21, 40, 13, 33, 33, NULL, 'Leaven and the Kingdom of Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of leaven as a metaphor for the kingdom of heaven, illustrating how it permeates and transforms. The identical phrasing regarding the woman hiding leaven in three measures of meal further strengthens this connection.', 'parallel', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 21, 46, 5, 6, 6, NULL, 'Leaven as a Transformative Agent', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of leaven as a transformative agent. In Luke, leaven is used to illustrate how a small amount can permeate a larger quantity, while in Corinthians, it warns that even a little leaven can affect the whole community.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 21, 52, 5, 23, 24, 'the whole was leavened', 'Sanctification and Transformation', 'This connection highlights the transformative process of sanctification. Both passages emphasize the idea of a complete change, with leaven representing the gradual permeation of holiness in 1 Thessalonians.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 21, 43, 4, 14, 14, NULL, 'Transformation and Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation, as both passages illustrate how something small can lead to significant change. The leaven in Luke represents the pervasive influence of the Kingdom of God, while the water in John symbolizes the life-giving power of Christ that transforms the believer.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
